Let's look at a simple Java program that prints 'Hello, World!' to the console. First, you would write the following code in a text editor:

public class HelloWorld {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println('Hello, World!');
    }
}

In this code, 'public class HelloWorld' defines a class named HelloWorld. The 'public static void main(String[] args)' line is the main method where the program starts executing. Inside the main method, 'System.out.println('Hello, World!');' is the command that prints the text to the console. Each part of the code has a specific role, and understanding this structure is essential for writing more complex programs in Java.

